            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Miller\u2019s life is one of structure and tangible results, a stark contrast to the ethereal, code-based world of his adopted city. Raised in a suburb of Cleveland, Ohio, pragmatism was in his DNA. His father, a union machinist, taught him the value of a well-made object and a hard day's work. David absorbed these lessons, but aimed to design the systems rather than operate the machines. He attended Purdue University, earning a degree in Industrial Engineering, and began a steady, methodical climb up the corporate ladder at various manufacturing firms across the Midwest.\n\nThe major turning point came fifteen years ago. A lucrative offer to become a senior manager for a medical device manufacturer in South San Francisco was too good to refuse. He and his then-wife, Sarah, moved west, trading Ohio\u2019s predictable seasons for the Bay Area\u2019s dynamic economy. They settled in a modest home in the Outer Sunset, a neighborhood whose fog and quietude felt more familiar than the city\u2019s sunnier, more chaotic districts.\n\nWhile David thrived professionally, mastering supply chains and optimizing production lines, his marriage frayed. The long hours his Director role demanded clashed with the a different pace of life Sarah had envisioned. Their divorce, five years ago, was amicable but left David feeling adrift. His anchor is his daughter, Chloe, now a sophomore at Boston University. Their weekly FaceTime calls are the highlight of his week.\n\nHis daily routine is a testament to his orderly mind. Up at 6:00 AM, he drives his Toyota Camry 10.8 miles south, navigating traffic with practiced patience. His day is a series of problems to be solved\u2014a stalled assembly line, a shipping delay, a personnel issue. He returns home to the quiet of his neighborhood, often taking a solitary walk along Ocean Beach as the fog rolls in. He has a few work friends and a neighbor he shares beers with, but his social circle is small.\n\nDavid\u2019s connection to San Francisco is functional. He respects the city's innovation but doesn't actively participate in its vibrant cultural life. His dream isn't to launch a startup, but to see his daughter graduate, perhaps find a partner who appreciates quiet evenings, and one day retire with enough money to buy a small workshop where he can build furniture\u2014returning, in a way, to the hands-on world his father taught him to value."
